FOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE IN ECUADOR
(Date of previous outbreak of foot and mouth disease in Ecuador reported to
the OIE: October 2005).
Translation of information received on 26 May 2006 from Dr Gustavo F. Mino
Verdesoto, Ministry of Agriculture and Livestock, Division of Animal Health
Emergencies and Epidemiological Surveillance, Quito:
Report date: 25 May 2006.
Reason for immediate notification: re-occurrence of a listed disease or
infection in a country.
Identification of agent: foot and mouth disease virus serotype O.
Date of start of the event: 15 May 2006.
Two outbreaks of foot and mouth disease serotype O have been reported in
cattle in 2 farms in Santo Domingo de los Colorados canton, in Pichincha
province. The outbreak in Quininde (10 cases out of 520 susceptible
animals) included young bulls of unknown origin acquired in the main market
of Santo Domingo. The outbreak in San Jacinto del Bua (6 cases out of 33
susceptible animals) has a bridle path which links this outbreak with the
Quininde outbreak located at a distance of approximately 3 km.
The diagnosis has been made by the National Veterinary Laboratory Izquieta
Perez by complement fixation test.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Santo Domingo de los Colorados appears to be located in the foothills of
the Andes at an altitude of 604 meters. You can see a map
at
<http://www.fallingrain.com/world/EC/18/Santo_Domingo_de_los_Colorados.html>
